John Edward: Language skills are critical for the world’s citizens
Scotland’s independent educational centres have a track record of academic excellence that has continued in 2018 with another set of extraordinary results in exams that is reinforced by the individual and collective successes gained in the fields of sport, art, music and other community projects.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these centres, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to deliver the best level of service to students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students to continue their higher education studies, for the career they choose and for the place they occupy as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement an adapted curriculum, it is observed that modern languages remain a popular and desired subject in the centers.
As Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a man in a language that he understands, the message comes to his head.
If you speak to him in his language, he comes to his heart.”
This is a powerful reminder that if you want to build relationships and build trust with people from other countries, you can’t rely solely on English.
If we take into account the recent results of this year’s exams, we can observe that languages are at the highest of the classification tables, with the rates of approved being the highest in independent schools.
In total, 68% of students who studied foreign languages obtained an A, the highest grade.
The data, collected from the 74 centers that are part of the SCIS, showed that 72% of the students obtained an A in Mandarin, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish also got an A.
This shows that Scotland’s independent schools support foreign languages as a fundamental competency that both children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
At present, it is considered that, as a subject, languages are at the same level as CTIM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and everywhere.
A 2014 survey by the United Kingdom’s Employment and Skills Commission found that, for employers’ reasons for the difficulties they encountered in filling jobs, 17 % were attributed to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly indispensable in preparing young people for their future careers.
The potential job opportunities that require languages are increasing, so these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career that someone chooses, if they have learned a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future thanks to a competition like this, which will last a lifetime.
Being able to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will allow that person to automatically advance to the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% of them did not speak any foreign language well enough to have a conversation, and the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, 15%, was French.
For this reason, investing in language teaching is now important for today’s children.
If they know several languages, especially those of developing economies, children will be equipped to have better opportunities to find quality employment.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Some centres will focus on the more classical modern languages, while others will teach the languages considered most important for the UK by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interests of a child, in independent schools you can always choose between several languages taught by specialized teaching staff in this field.
Scotland’s independent education centres devote all their efforts to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future holds for them.
At the moment, it is undeniable that, in a global business environment, languages continue to have a vital importance for the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages should be considered "competences for international communication".
Independent schools will continue to offer these options, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
It has to be done.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Colleges.
