The National Trust spies on the secret life of bats
This new research, which has been carried out in a state in the Scottish Highlands, attempts to discover how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
Everything that is discovered is expected to shed more light on the behavior of the only flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities.
The study, conducted by the National Trust for Scotland, will follow the common bats and sopranos, as well as the riverside bats of Daubenton and long-eared browns of the Inverewe gardens at Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed at strategic locations on the property to track bat activities during the season.
