Red Tide Update: Concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota Decline
The new report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows an overall reduction in red tide concentrations in areas of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, irregular flowering conditions are being reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting a reduction in concentrations.
The red tide bloom extends approximately 130 miles of coastline from Pinellas County in the north to Lee County in the south.
Irregular parcels can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer places compared to last week.
Red tide has also been detected in Pasco County.
Over the past week, average concentrations have been reported in Pinellas County and its coast, low-to-high concentrations on the Hillsborough County coast, bottom-to-high concentrations in Manatee County, bottom-to-high concentrations in Sarasota County and its coast, bottom-to-middle concentrations in Charlotte County, and bottom-to-high concentrations in Charlotte County.
Respiratory irritation problems continue to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
There have been no reports of respiratory irritation problems in Northwest Florida over the past week.
